funding_code: RBCS ENTERPRISE GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will help to fund technical assistance to provide a Strategic Visioning Workshop, 5-Year Strategic Plan, and downtown merchant technical assistance for Entiat, WA and Waterville, WA. The NCW Economic Development District will undertake these efforts. The primary beneficiaries of the project will be the businesses and entrepreneurs of Entiat, WA and Waterville, WA. Grant funds will be used for NCWEDD staff time and to contract with Downtown Strategies for planning and implementation of this project. At least four small businesses will be assisted with long term effects leading to job creation.

funding_code: RBCS DEVELOPMENT GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
naics_description: ADMINISTRATION OF URBAN PLANNING AND COMMUNITY AND RURAL DEVELOPMENT
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will help fund a five-year strategic plan to downtown merchants in Entiat and Waterville, Washington, located in Chelan County. The project will include a boots on the ground analysis, stakeholder input, and community collaboration along with customized market research to enhance economic vitality. The Our Valley Our Futures primary goal will be to revitalize the downtown areas of Entiat and Waterville, Washington by implementing technical assistance in each community through inactive marketing, via handouts and virtually to support training in these areas. Post projections anticipates job creation and that as many as five small businesses will be assisted.

funding_code: RBCS ENTERPRISE GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Other Services (except Public Administration) (81)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will help finance the Planning and Development of the Historic Downtown Chelan Revitalization Project based in Chelan County. The project will serve four downtown Chelan business owners and will help in revitalizing the area per a post Covid initiative. The Historic Downtown Chelan Associations primary goal will be to increase accessibility for current businesses within the area with the construction of additional sidewalks and added infrastructure to better support events and activities that bring people to the area. It is anticipated that as many as four businesses will be assisted along with twenty-one jobs created and twenty-six jobs saved.

funding_code: RBCS ENTERPRISE GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Other Services (except Public Administration) (81)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will help to fund the technical assistance project for the Lake Chelan Grape Growers Association dba Lake Chelan Wine Valley for the city of Chelan,Washington. The Lake Chelan Grape Growers Association will undertake a three year strategic marketing initiative to drive tourism to the area. The primary beneficiaries of the project will be the businesses and entrepreneurs of Lake Chelan Wine Valley. Grant and matching funds will be used for content creation, social media, event planning, website design, brochure creation, print advertising, community signage creation, and project management. At least eight small businesses will be assisted, and 44 jobs created.

funding_code: COMMUNITY FACILITY (DIRECT AND GUARANTEED LOANS)
naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to replace an aging hospital and health care facility. Funding consists of a Community Facilities Direct Loan of $96,330,000 and 80 percent Guarantee Loan of $40,146,127. The new facility will have modern building offering more services, capacity and health care providers in the Community of Moses Lake and the Grant County service area. The current facility has been added to and built on since the original building in the 1940s. This has been an issue for a community that is growing, working to keep up with health care demands and outsources to other hospitals due to this dilemma. Samaritan Hospital is in Grant County, Washington, United States. The population is estimated at 20,366 per the 2010 census. Moses Lake is the County Seat in a census poverty community and therefore granted to go within 10 percent above the population limit for Community Facilities. Total cost of the project is $163.5 million.

naics_industry_sector: Accommodation and Food Services (72)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to refinance an interim loan made to fund the acquisition of the Guesthouse Montesano a small hotel located in Montesano, Grays Harbor County, WA. The borrower is Delta Guide Meridian Inc. This acquisition will save seven jobs in this high unemployment area and facilitate the continued provision of hospitality services in a rural area. USDA Rural Development is providing an 80 percent guarantee on this loan through UniBank.

program: Rural Energy for America Program Renewable Energy Systems and Energy Efficiency Improvement Loans and Grants
funding_code: MAND.ENERGY EFFIC IMPROV GRANTS UNDER $20,000

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to assist Alexander Dunsire purchase and install an LED lighting retrofit of a commercial building leased by Dominate Print LLC from Alexander Dunsire. The project is located in a high poverty census tract in downtown Aberdeen, Washington. This project will realize $1,500 per year in savings, and will save 12,714 kilowatt hours (kWh) per year, which is enough electricity to power one home.

funding_code: RBCS ENTERPRISE GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Educational Services (61)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used for business support and technical assistance in Seattle Washington, King County. It will provide technical assistance to rural farmers and food entrepreneurs at any stage from launch to growth. It is anticipated that as many as six small business will be assisted and 10 new jobs and 10 jobs saved.

funding_code: RBCS ENTERPRISE GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Educational Services (61)
naics_description: ALL OTHER MISCELLANEOUS SCHOOLS AND INSTRUCTION
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will fund the provision of technical assistance and training for emerging entrepreneurs and early stage microenterprises in Island and Skagit Counties, Washington. The Center for Inclusive Entrepreneurship, a non-profit organization, will undertake these efforts through its North Cascades Community Enterprise Program. The program is comprised of three phases: outreach throughout the service area to identify and recruit individuals likely to benefit, the provision of business training via an 8-hour course, and one-on-one counseling to a smaller group of promising beneficiaries identified during the broader business training course. At least five businesses will be assisted, and the project is expected to create and save at least five jobs.

funding_code: DISCRETION ASSIST MICROPENTERPRENUERS
naics_industry_sector: Educational Services (61)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide technical assistance to rural microentrepreneurs, primarily in Clallam, Island, Jefferson, King, Kitsap, Pierce, San Juan, Skagit, Snohomish, and Whatcom Counties. Technical assistance efforts on the part of the grantee are intended to promote small business growth and development in rural communities, leading to job creation and retainage.

naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development Investment will be used to fund the design and construction of the chlorination of Well 2 for the Klickitat County Port District #1. This project will increase the available water supply for businesses located at the Dallesport Industrial Park, that currently has only one operating well for businesses and fire protection. funding_code: ELECTRIC FFB - OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to connect 487 consumers, and build 37 miles of line. Benton Rural Electricis headquartered in Prosser, Wash. It serves approximately 14,000 customers over 1,774 miles of line in Benton and Lewis counties in south central Washington.

funding_code: RURAL ENERGY SAVINGS PROGRAM (RESP)
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to finance an energy efficiency relending program to finance projects that include Smart-Inverter rooftop solar for residences & small business and Dispatchable In-home battery storage.

funding_code: COMMUNITY CONNECTIVITY-ORIENTED GTS
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to construct an approximately 9 mile Fiber-to-the Premises system to benefit358 residents and3 businesses in the Point Roberts, Whatcom County, Washington service area. Subscribers will have access to service up to 1 Gbps, expanding access to economic, educational, health care, and public safety opportunities. A community center will be provided in a mobile facility placed as part of this project where residents can access the Internet free of charge for at least two years.

funding_code: DISTANCE LEARNING- GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase equipment that will allow Centro De Servicios Comunitarios (CSC). CSC Yakima (the CSC Tech Hub) to provide support for both Telemedicine and Remote Learning services on the Yakima Reservation. Key among the telemedicine services will be referral to two Yakima Valley Farm Workers Clinics (YVFW) treatment centers specializing in behavioral health including Substance Abuse and alcoholism with extended services provided for the families of those afflicted. Distance Learning opportunities will be provided across multiple communities from two end user locations to support enhanced English Language skills, computer literacy, remedial academic tutoring and educational enrichment courses of study in science, technology, engineering, and math (STEM) fields. This project will reach approximately 9,700 community residents.

funding_code: DLT GRANTS - SUBSTANCE USE DISORDER - EDUCATIONAL
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to serve students and members of the Davenport, Hatton, Lind and Ritzville communities. Proposed hub/end-user sites for this project will be the Davenport High School, Davenport Elementary/Junior High, Lind Elementary School, Ritzville Grade School, Lind-Ritzville Middle School, and Lind-Ritzville High School. This project will bring telecommunications equipment into these schools and also allow the districts to expand College In the Classroom programs, share teacher resources, expand professional development, expand remote learning capabilities, and begin offering students and community members access to telemedicine opportunities. This project will impact an estimated 1,500 rural community members.

funding_code: DISTANCE LEARNING- GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to connect 12 rural dental clinics in the states of Washington and Montana through state-of-the-art tele-dentistry equipment to the University of Washington School of Dentistry. It will provide much greater access to instructors while caring for patients and expands the ability for teaching dentistry students to successfully learn oral health care while training at rural or underserved locations. The direct service area includes 57,000 residents, but the project is expected to have an impact on surrounding areas as well, with a total affected population of 890,000.

funding_code: GUARANTEED B&I 3% FEE LOAN
naics_industry_sector: Accommodation and Food Services (72)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment via a rural business loan guarantee will be used to fund the refinance of an existing hotel by the Borrowers, Omak Peppertree LLC and Santillanes Omak LLC. Property was previously financed with a USDA loan where rates increased to over 7 percent and rising. They quickly refinanced into a conventional 5 year loan with US Bank with a 4.9 percent interest rate. They are now seeking long term financing with Wheatland Bank. The proposed loan is a fixed for the first 10 years at 4.45 percent, 25-year term, and the Agency is providing an 80% guaranty.

funding_code: PERSISTENT POVERTY RBCS BUSINESS ENTERPRISE GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will help to fund technical assistance for the broadband feasibility study work initiated by the Okanogan County/Colville Confederated Tribes Broadband Action Team. The Economic Alliance of Okanogan County will undertake these efforts. The primary beneficiaries of the project will be the businesses and entrepreneurs of Okanogan County. Grant and matching funds will be used to hire a consultant to complete the broadband feasibility study. At least 3 small businesses will be assisted.

funding_code: PERSISTENT POVERTY RBCS BUSINESS ENTERPRISE GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will help to fund technical assistance to expand the Small Business Resource Center in Omak, Washington. The Economic Alliance will undertake these efforts. The primary beneficiaries of the project will be the businesses and entrepreneurs of Okanogan County. Grant and matching funds will be used to pay for staffing and equipment for the Small Business Center. At least five small businesses will be assisted.

funding_code: PERSISTENT POVERTY RBCS BUSINESS ENTERPRISE GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will help to fund a feasibility study for a fire hall and training center in the the Town of Loomis, Washington. The Okanogan County will undertake these efforts. The primary beneficiaries of the project will be the businesses and entrepreneurs of Loomis. Grant and matching funds will be used to pay a contractor to conduct the feasibility study. At least eight farmers/ranchers and four small businesses will be assisted.

funding_code: PERSISTENT POVERTY RBCS BUSINESS ENTERPRISE GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will help to fund technical assistance for the Tonasket Public Art Project in Tonasket, Washington. Okanogan Highlands Alliance, a local non-profit will undertake these efforts. The primary beneficiaries of the project will be the businesses and entrepreneurs of Tonasket, Washington that will see an increase in tourism. Grant and matching funds will be used to make the town more visually beautiful, attracting customers to local businesses and stimulating economic growth in the area. At least 5 small businesses will be assisted and 2 jobs created.

funding_code: LOCAL AGRICULTURE MARKET RESOURCE PROGRAM (LAMP) VALUE-ADDED PRODUCER GRANTS - COVID
naics_industry_sector: Agriculture, Forestry, Fishing and Hunting (11)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to finance a working capital Value-Added Covid Producer Grant. Funds for inventory, marketing, workshop, printing, display racks, advertising, and fulfilment to expand from wholesale markets into retail markets for certified organic vegetable, herb and flower packaged seeds all over the Country. Ana K. Mines is an independent producer located in Okanogan County, Washington.

funding_code: COMMUNITY FACILITY (DIRECT AND GUARANTEED LOANS)
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to construct a new City Services Building/Community Center/Emergency management facility to replace an ageing and unsafe City Hall with a modern facility that will also support public works, law enforcement, and EMS services. The Community has been impacted severely from back to back wild fire disasters. The proposed new essential safety community facility will provide a central emergency coordination center for town of Twisp law enforcement and state/federal first responders to effectively coordinate any future disasters/emergency response efforts.

funding_code: CF GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to replace an aging and unsafe fire station and public works building with a modern facility that will function as public works, food bank, and Emegency Medical Services services combined. The community has been impacted severely from year to year with devastating fires and other natural disasters and so the proposed facility aims to address those needs as well. Conconully is in Okanogan County. The population is estimated at 210 per the 2010 census.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase a 14-foot refrigerated box truck with a tuck away lift gate. This truck will replace their current truck that has over 550,000 miles which is unreliable, and no longer refrigerates. Darrington Food Bank Foundation drives about 1500 miles per month picking up items to stock and make available in their food bank. Now they will have a truck that is reliable and refrigerates so they can pick up and deliver perishable items. Their service area includes Town of Darrington, northeastern Snohomish and southwestern Skagit counties, including tribal members of the Sauk-Suiattle, Tulalip, and Lummi Tribes.

Hunters is an unincorporated community established in 1884 in rural Stevens County.

funding_code: RBCS ENTERPRISE GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Educational Services (61)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to fund comprehensive planning efforts for creating a model for food processing facilities that can be constructed in South East Washington State to serve produce growers. Washington State University will undertake these efforts. Specifically, the applicant will use grant and matching funds to plan, gather data, and perform a market analysis, complete a food safety plan and create standard operating procedures, build a pilot processing line for minimally processed produce, and perform a financial analysis related to the likely success of other projects following this model. At least five small and emerging businesses will be assisted.

funding_code: RBCS ENTERPRISE GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Other Services (except Public Administration) (81)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used by the nonprofit Northwest Cooperative Development Center to further rural economic development in central Ore. The nonprofit will use the USDA grant to provide technical assistance and training to small and emerging businesses in Bend, Terrebonne, and Madras. The technical assistance will include support with project planning, business counseling and training, market research, developing feasibility studies, creating professional and technical reports, and improving producer services. Overall, the nonprofit will support two farms, two small businesses, and one small agriculture co-op through its training program and will save six jobs in these rural central Ore. communities.

funding_code: RURAL COOPERATIVE DEVELOPMENT GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Professional, Scientific, and Technical Services (54)
naics_description: ADMINISTRATIVE MANAGEMENT AND GENERAL MANAGEMENT CONSULTING SERVICES
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used by Northwest Cooperative Development Center to reopen and rebuild local economies through the creation and retention of cooperatives, convene networks of the cooperatives to encourage collaboration and mutual support, assist cooperative leaders in understanding and improving their physical conditions and capital investments, and innovate in the methods and processes for delivering quality technical assistance efficiently to growing audiences.

program: Rural Energy for America Program Renewable Energy Systems and Energy Efficiency Improvement Loans and Grants
funding_code: MAND. RENEW ENERFY SYSTEMS GRANTS UNDER $20,000
naics_industry_sector: Accommodation and Food Services (72)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase and install a 14.85 kW solar array on Swantown Inn & Spa LLC, a family owned business in Olympia, Washington. This project will replace 14,850 kWh (45%) per year and realize $1,700 in energy savings per year. The purpose of this funding program is to assist farmers, ranchers, and rural small businesses in developing renewable energy systems, and in making energy-efficiency improvements to their operations.

funding_code: DISCRETION ASSIST MICROPENTERPRENUERS
naics_industry_sector: Retail Trade (44-45)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide technical assistance to rural microentrepreneurs, primarily in Thurston, Mason, Lewis, Pacific, and Grays Harbor Counties. Technical assistance efforts on the part of the grantee are intended to promote small business growth and development in rural communities, leading to job creation and retainage.

funding_code: SMALL SOCIALLY DISADVANTAGED PRODUCER GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Other Services (except Public Administration) (81)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to advise and educate members of socially-disadvantaged groups, specifically co-ops. Advisory technical assistance will be in the form of cooperative business model education, feasibility research, cost analysis, strategic and business planning, board coaching and training, capitalization planning, accounting assistance, operations development, marketing/branding, and first response. Throughout this work, funds will be used to ensure that technical assistance is accompanied by interpreters or translations, when needed, to fully involve members of the co-ops. The activities proposed in this application are advisory services performed for the benefit of the following socially-disadvantaged groups, who have been subjected to racial, ethnic, or gender prejudice because of their identities as members of these groups without regard to their individual qualities. This project will assist at least 12 Cooperatives and 12 Socially Disadvantaged Groups.

funding_code: RBCS ENTERPRISE NATIVE AMERICAN GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Finance and Insurance (52)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to help fund training and technical assistance efforts for small businesses and entrepreneurs on the Lummi Reservation and in other rural areas of Whatcom County, Washington. Lummi Community Development Financial Institution, a non-profit business technical assistance provider and lender, will undertake these efforts. Specific assistance offered will include one-on-one consultation, organization of workshops, conferences, and seminars, peer-to-peer mentoring, business skill development experiences, and access to capital through the applicants affiliated loan programs, including the Small Business Administrations Payment Protection Program. At least five small and emerging businesses will be assisted and the project is expected to create or save at least 10 jobs.

funding_code: RBCS DEVELOPMENT GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will help fund comprehensive research and planning efforts to identify, prepare for, and recruit rural small businesses that would be good candidates to locate in the subject city. The City of Blaine will carry out the purpose of this grant with the help of a qualified consultant. Grant and matching funds will be used to build a database of potential retail businesses that would be well-suited to Blaine, develop a marketing guide for distribution to partners and potential recruits, and execute a campaign to attract potential retailers. At least four small and emerging businesses will be assisted.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to fund technical assistance related to providing energy audits to agricultural producers and rural small businesses in rural Whatcom County, Wash. The applicant, the Port of Bellingham, is a utility provider in the County. The applicant and its partners plan to provide at least 30 energy audits to eligible businesses.

The grantee will realize 8,870 kilowatt hours (kWh) in energy offsets and $1,037 each year in savings.

naics_industry_sector: Agriculture, Forestry, Fishing and Hunting (11)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used for supplies, contractual expenses associated with processing, packaging, and marketing for a line of grass-fed beef smoked products. Matheson Farms LLC located in Whatcom County, Washington is an independent producer and socially disadvantaged farm.

funding_code: LOCAL AGRICULTURE MARKET RESOURCE PROGRAM (LAMP) VALUE-ADDED PRODUCER GRANTS - COVID
naics_industry_sector: Agriculture, Forestry, Fishing and Hunting (11)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to finance a working capital Value-Added Covid Producer Grant. The grant and matching will be used for packaging, marketing, and promotional expenses associated with sales to new customers at farm stores, restaurants, grocery stores and at the farmers market, storage, and distribution facilities for market expansion to sell more locally produced beef. Ebos, Inc. in Whatcom County, Washington which is an independent producer will increase business revenue by $160,000 and increase customer base by 379. This project is anticipated to save one job and create four jobs.

funding_code: LOCAL AGRICULTURE MARKET RESOURCE PROGRAM (LAMP) VALUE-ADDED PRODUCER GRANTS - COVID
naics_industry_sector: Agriculture, Forestry, Fishing and Hunting (11)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to for working capital. Funds will be used for labor, supplies, and contractual expenses associated with processing, packaging, and marketing for products made from raw cows milk. Sales direct to consumers through five farmers markets targeting Skagit, Snohomish and Whatcom Counties, and wholesale sales to 15 individual retail supermarket accounts. Steensma Creamery is an independent woman-owned producer start-up business in Whatcom County, WA. Business revenue will increase by $504,215.00and increase customer base by 29,400. This project is anticipated to create two jobs. There was also an In-Kind contribution of $52,500 and Commodity match of $53,239.

naics_industry_sector: Educational Services (61)
naics_description: ALL OTHER MISCELLANEOUS SCHOOLS AND INSTRUCTION
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used for the construction of a 1,152 square foot traditionally built in the longhouse fashion with cedar shingle roof and round ply construction and limited partial walls, on the Northwest Indian College South Campus. This outdoor learning pavilion will promote indigenous self-determination and knowledge through education.Population of the community where the Northwest Indian College is located (Lummi Nation Reservation) has a population of 4,706 which they will serve. They also have satellite classes around the Northwest offering remote learning classes.

funding_code: REAP-MANDATORY RENEW ENERGY SYST GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Agriculture, Forestry, Fishing and Hunting (11)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to help fund the purchase and installation of a 198 kilowatt (kW) photo voltaic solar array. Black Star Ranch is an established hops farm located in rural Yakima County. The grantee will reduce their energy consumption by 114.4 percent, which is enough electricity to power one home. The purpose of this funding program is to assist farmers, ranchers, and rural small businesses in developing renewable energy systems and making energy-efficiency improvements to their operations.

The purpose of this funding program is to assist the rural small businesses in developing renewable energy systems and making energy-efficiency improvements to their operations.

funding_code: VALUE-ADDED PRODUCER DEVELOPMENT GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Manufacturing (31-33)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to acquire cabernet franc grapes to make wine in Yakima County, Washington . The goal of this project for this Independent Producer is to increase sales through the expansion of the companys market and product line. Because these products demand higher margins and prices than standard grapes, it will likely have a direct effect on the sustainability of the company for the near future. Tasks for this project include advertising, intake of delivered grapes, and the processing of grapes into the value-added product. It is anticipated that as many as three individuals will be assisted and more than three jobs created.

funding_code: PERSISTENT POVERTY RBCS BUSINESS ENTERPRISE GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to help fund technical assistance efforts to revitalize, regrow and reinvent the downtowns of Coulee, Elmber and Okanogan cities in Washington. North Central Washington Economic Development District, a local non-profit business and technical assistance provider, will undertake these efforts. North Central Washington Economic Development District will partner with Downtown Strategies, a strategic planning business. Together they will provide a 5- year strategic plan, visioning and training workshops and resource connections. At least eight small and emerging business will be assisted and the project is expected to create or save at least 30 jobs.

funding_code: RBCS ENTERPRISE GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Other Services (except Public Administration) (81)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to assist with the development and expansion of small and emerging businesses throughout Chelan County. This grant will fund the marketing and related expenses needed to create, produce, market and execute efforts to drive wine tourism to the area during its off season. Funds will be used to contract with a marketing professional, advertising, production of "valley guide map" and monthly banners for city light poles. Lake Chelan Grape Growers Association, a local non profit, will undergo these efforts. Local businesses and entrepreneurs will be the primary beneficiaries of these efforts. Eleven local businesses have verified they will benefit from this project; 74 jobs will be sustained and at least 28 jobs will be created.

funding_code: RBCS ENTERPRISE GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to assist with the planning and development of an ADA crosswalk and sidewalk that connects the downtown businesses to a new parking lot expansion. The City of Bridgeport, Washington will undertake these efforts. The primary beneficiaries of the project will be the small and emerging businesses in Bridgeport, Washington who will benefit by increasing safe access to their store fronts and aligning with the Citys 5-year revitalization plan. Grant funds will be used for planning and construction of the crosswalk/sidewalk. Five small businesses have verified they will be assisted by this project which will save 25 jobs.

funding_code: RBCS ENTERPRISE GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to help fund the replacement of signage in the City of Bridgeport, WA located along the Columbia River. The City of Bridgeport will undertake these efforts. The City is requesting funding to assist with the purchase and installation of their town "Welcome" signs that burned during the FEMA declared Pearl Hill Fire where 20+ homes were lost. The primary beneficiaries of the project will be businesses and entrepreneurs of Bridgeport as well as visitors of the City. Grant and Matchings funds will be used to fund the Major project elements which include; contract with a private firm to fabricate and install two signs. Five small businesses will be assisted.

funding_code: CF ARP EMERGENCY RURAL HEALTH CARE GRANTS - TRACK 1 & 2
naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to expand the clinical footprint of Summit Pacific Medical Center (SPMC) for increased capacity of COVID-19 testing and treatment. Expansion will be achieved by shifting current administrative space to six-exam rooms with a dedicated waiting room to support medical surge capacity for urgent care and specialty services. The current clinical space for specialty and urgent care does not provide capacity to isolate patients who present with respiratory or other COVID like symptoms. This renovation project will provide a dedicated space for patients who need specialty services away from the urgent care clinic with an isolated waiting room to minimize exposure. Quartermaster Heights Water Associationserves about 59 persons and 28 connections, all located on Vashon Island, in rural King County.

borrower_name: Pacific Northwest Pollution Prevention Resource Center
funding_code: (WWA PROGRAM AREA) TAT GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide technical assistance training in Fats, Oils, and Greases (FOG) abatement to small, rural communities throughout the western United States. Specifically, Pacific Northwest Pollution Prevention Resource Center will: (1) Organize and conduct 20 FOG Abatement Technical Trainings across the nation, 10 virtual and 10 in-person, all with interactive components, and to create and provide a new access-based tool so trainees can establish and maintain a data-driven FOG Abatement Program; (2) Enhance the National Resource Reference Guide , the online, supplemental information resource that programs use for further clarification, details, instruction and best management practices following training to enhance implementation of their FOG abatement program; and, (3) Measure Success of programs trained in FY21 and past years.

funding_code: GUARANTEED B&I 3% FEE LOAN
naics_industry_sector: Real Estate and Rental and Leasing (53)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to acquire a multiuse commercial property in rural King County, Washington. The borrowers are SLK Investment Property LLC and Moon & Sun LLC. There are 10 tenants on the premises, and the current lessor of the convenience store and fuel station is the co-borrower, Moon & Sun LLC. The borrowers are contributing $95,400 towards the project. The proposed loan is fixed for five years at 4.50 percent, 25-year term, and the Agency is providing an 80 percent guaranty. The 10 businesses that are located within the facility will be assisted.

The project is expected create 2 jobs, save 2 jobs and includes a $250,000 in-kind match from the grantee.

funding_code: RBCS ENTERPRISE GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to fund the provision of technical assistance and training for emerging entrepreneurs and early stage microenterprises in Whitman, Asotin, Columbia and Garfield counties, Washington. The Center for Inclusive Entrepreneurship, a non-profit organization, will undertake these efforts with Spokane Independent Metropolitan Business Alliance s online marketplace and the Pullman Small Business Development Center s community outreach and business technical assistance The program is comprised of three phases: outreach throughout the service area to identify and recruit individuals likely to benefit, the provision of business training via an 8-hour course, and one-on-one counseling to a smaller group of promising beneficiaries identified during the broader business training course. At least six businesses will be assisted, and the project is expected to create and save at least six jobs.

funding_code: RBCS ENTERPRISE GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Educational Services (61)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to help fund training and technical assistance efforts for existing and prospective rural farmers and food businesses in Skagit County. Seattle Economic Development Fund, based out of Seattle will use the grant to support technical assistance services, including free one-on-one business coaching, on-demand business training tailored to the food and farm industry, access to capital, market connections, and referrals to other business support centers. At least five small and emerging businesses will be assisted throughout Skagit County and the project is expected to create or save at least 14 jobs.

funding_code: DISCRETION RURAL MICROPENTERPR DEV ORG
naics_industry_sector: Educational Services (61)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to help fund training and technical assistance efforts for rural farmers, prospective rural farmers, and food businesses in Skagit County. This project will support technical assistance services, including free one-on-one business coaching, on-demand business training tailored to the food and farm industry, access to capital, market connections, and referrals to other business support centers.

funding_code: GUARANTEED B&I 3% FEE LOAN
naics_industry_sector: Accommodation and Food Services (72)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to refinance debt for the purchase acquisition of the Silverdale Quality Inn located in Silverdale, Washington. This loan will save 14 new jobs.

funding_code: RBCS ENTERPRISE GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Other Services (except Public Administration) (81)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide technical assistance to at least fifteen existing and new agriculture and food sector businesses to support farm business management, farm succession planning and land access. Emphasis will be placed on serving beginning, under resourced and BIPOC farmers. Assistance will include pathways to farm and food business expansion, feasibility analysis for value-added products, market development, regulatory compliance, farm succession planning, land access, and consultation and evaluation of business finance options. This project is expected to create 5 jobs.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to assist in the purchase and installation of a 45 kW solar PV system. The recipient is an agriculture producer located in rural Klickitat County. This project will replace 55,080 kWh (28 percent) per year and realize $104,999 of saving per year. The purpose of this funding program is to assist farmers, ranchers, and rural small businesses in developing renewable energy systems, and in making energy-efficiency improvements to their operations.

funding_code: CF ARP EMERGENCY RURAL HEALTH CARE GRANTS - TRACK 1 & 2
naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to renovate 1,167 square feet of existing interior space related to food preparation and service at the hospital. The renovation will provide for two additional workstations, streamline the checkout, replace the salad bar with a sandwich prep table; install a walk-in cooler, walk -in freezer, and additional dry storage. Additionally, they will construct a 663 square feet addition to a house a dishwashing galley that will provide a separate entrance from the kitchen for receiving dirty dishes reducing the potential of COVID-19 patient trays, dishes, and utensils to be cleaned prior to being returned to service in the kitchen. Public Hospital District #1 of Klickitat County is one of 40 Critical Access Hospitals (CAHs) in Washington State. CAHs are small hospitals with fewer than 25 beds located in rural areas.

program: Rural Energy for America Program Renewable Energy Systems and Energy Efficiency Improvement Loans and Grants
funding_code: MAND. RENEW ENERFY SYSTEMS GRANTS UNDER $20,000
naics_industry_sector: Retail Trade (44-45)

funding_code: CF ARP EMERGENCY RURAL HEALTH CARE GRANTS - TRACK 1 & 2
naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
naics_description: RESCUE AND AMBULANCE SERVICE - EQUIPMENT BUILDING
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase an ambulance and associated equipment. The funding will enhance Lewis County Fire District # 3s ability to service the community of Mossyrock and surrounding area through distribution of COVID-19 vaccinations, COVID-19 testing, and implementation of the Community Health Triage Program while significantly improving the safety of the EMS staff and their ability to respond to emergency calls. The ambulance that will be replaced added unnecessary risk for the EMS staff as plastic and blankets were used to separate the driver from the patient in the back. The new ambulance is the latest and greatest with a safe environment for the EMS crew and the patient.

funding_code: CF GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
naics_description: OTHER PUBLIC BUILDING & IMPROVEMENT RELATED SERVICES
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to to repair/replace the roof with insulation to reduce the heating costs of the old building and stop leakage. The Roxy, which is 100 years old, is the only theater still active in East Lewis County, and plays host of live theater productions, childrens theater productions as well as first run movies. Located in the heart of the rural community of Morton along its historic main street, The Roxy Theater plays an important part in the local history as well as offering the opportunity for making connections with friends and loved ones. The Roxy Theater is an integral part of the community and creates a welcoming environment for all. Repairs made to the building will make the theater more sustainable to ensure this community treasure lasts for many generations to come.

funding_code: PERSISTENT POVERTY RBCS BUSINESS ENTERPRISE GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to help fund technical assistance efforts for existing and disadvantaged small businesses within Okanogan County, Washington. There will be an emphasis on assisting businesses that have been impacted by the Covid-19 pandemic. Economic Alliance, a non-profit business and technical assistance provider, will undertake these efforts. Specific assistance offered will include, one-on-one small business assistance, organization of trainings, webinars and resource connections. At least five small and emerging businesses will be assisted and the project is expected to create or save at least 43 jobs.

funding_code: PERSISTENT POVERTY RBCS BUSINESS ENTERPRISE GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to assist with the development and expansion of small and emerging businesses in Okanogan County by funding the fees for professional services necessary for the planning and development of turning the Loup Loup Ski Bowl from a four month resort to a twelve month recreation space. The Loup Loup Ski Education Foundation will undertake these efforts. The primary beneficiaries of the project will be the businesses and entrepreneurs of Okanogan County. Grant funds will be used to hire a consultant to complete a business plan, feasibility study, and perform market research. Five small businesses have verified they will be assisted and expect to create twelve jobs and support at least three.

borrower_name: NCW SPORTS RINK AND EVENT CENTER
funding_code: PERSISTENT POVERTY RBCS BUSINESS ENTERPRISE GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to fund the professional fees for a feasibility study for the Pateros Rink & Event Center in Pateros, WA in a distressed community. The Rink & Event Center will undertake these efforts. The primary beneficiaries of the project will be the businesses and entrepreneurs of Pateros, WA and Okanogan County. Grant funds will be used to hire a consultant to complete the feasibility study. Four small businesses have verified they will be assisted with two jobs created and 19 jobs saved.

funding_code: CF ARP EMERGENCY RURAL HEALTH CARE GRANTS - TRACK 1 & 2
naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to allow Douglas Okanogan County Fire District #15 replace two of their ambulances that are past their useful life. During the COVID-19 pandemic the ambulances lacked adequate ventilation, air filtration and a separated patient - driver compartments. The vehicles also have been plagued with multiple mechanical failures. Approximately 9,459 residents reside in the Douglas Okanogan County Fire District 15 area including residents of the cities of Brewster, Pateros, Methow CDP, Bridgeport, and portions of both unincorporated Okanogan and Douglas Counties. The two new ambulances will allow the district to address these air quality safety issues as well as utilize a new molded surface making decontamination of the units better and faster between patients.

funding_code: CF ARP EMERGENCY RURAL HEALTH CARE GRANTS - TRACK 1 & 2
naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to upgrade needed heating, ventilation and air conditioning (HVAC) including air handlers and electrical systems in the building and demolition and removal of the older HVAC system installed in 1952. This project will ensure adequate ventilation to aid in the removal of airborne pathogens and benefit 11,500 residents in Okanogan County including the 1,031 residents of the city of Tonasket.

funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to improve the Waste water Treatment Plant (WWTP) in the Town of Friday Harbor for required improvements to the plant to address performance issues, aging equipment, future flow and loading capacity, and current standards for redundancy and reliability. The WWTP serves a population of approximately 2,162 rural residents plus waste water from the University of Washington Laboratories. The most recent major upgrades to the plant occurred in 2004 when the plant was converted to a Sequencing Batch Reactor (SBR), 2018 when a Tertiary Filter was installed, and present day when a new headworks is being constructed. The primary components of the existing WWTP consist of new dual mechanical screens and grit removal basins, two individual SBR basins, two post-equalization basins, and UV disinfection.

funding_code: RURAL COOPERATIVE DEVELOPMENT GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Professional, Scientific, and Technical Services (54)
naics_description: ADMINISTRATIVE MANAGEMENT AND GENERAL MANAGEMENT CONSULTING SERVICES
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to assist Northwest Cooperative Development Center reopen and rebuild local economies through the creation and retention of cooperatives. This project will convene network cooperatives to encourage collaboration and mutual support, assist leaders in understanding, and improving their physical conditions and capital investments, and innovate in the methods and processes for delivering quality technical assistance efficiently to growing audiences. Four jobs will be created and 62 jobs will be saved.

program: Rural Energy for America Program Renewable Energy Systems and Energy Efficiency Improvement Loans and Grants
funding_code: REAP-MANDATORY RENEW ENERGY SYST GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Management of Companies and Enterprises (55)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to assist a rural small businesses in developing a renewable energy system. FP Yelm LLC is an existing business located in rural Thurston County. Project funds will be used for the purchase and installation of a 53.93 kilowatt hours (kWh) solar array. This project will realize $6,108 per year in savings and will replace 53,150 kWh per year which is enough to energize five single family homes.

funding_code: DISCRETION RURAL MICROPENTERPR DEV ORG
naics_industry_sector: Retail Trade (44-45)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide technical assistance to rural microentrepreneurs, primarily in Thurston, Mason, Lewis, Pacific, and Grays Harbor Counties. Technical assistance efforts on the part of the grantee are intended to promote small business growth and development in rural communities, leading to the creation and retention of 22 jobs.

funding_code: SMALL SOCIALLY DISADVANTAGED PRODUCER GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Other Services (except Public Administration) (81)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to advise and educate members of socially-disadvantaged groups, specifically involving cooperatives and cooperative business model development. Technical assistance will include co-op business model education, feasibility research, cost analysis, strategic and business planning, board/management/member coaching and training, capitalization planning, accounting assistance, operations development, marketing and branding, and first response. Funds will be used to ensure technical assistance is accompanied by interpreters or translations, when needed, to fully involve members of the co-ops. This project will benefit socially-disadvantaged groups who have been subjected to racial, ethnic, or gender prejudice because of their identities as members of these groups without regard to their individual and collective qualities of excellence.

naics_industry_sector: Professional, Scientific, and Technical Services (54)
naics_description: RESEARCH AND DEVELOPMENT IN THE PHYSICAL, ENGINEERING, AND LIFE SCIENCES
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used by Northwest Indian College to purchase Scientific and Safety Equipment for an Educational Boat. The boat will allow students to learn how to navigate waters, understand the complex marine ecosystem, and look at the impacts and stressors of the industrialized world on this critically important marine and cultural waterscape. The vessel will also provide space for oral histories and storytelling, which will enhance and ground the research and teaching experience. It will be able to handle a classroom size of up to 25 students with an overnight capacity of 4-5 for longer voyages. The community where the Northwest Indian College is located (Lummi Nation Reservation) has a population of 4,706 which they will serve. They also have satellite classes around the Northwest offering remote learning classes.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to support small-business development for approximately 40 farmers, ranchers, fishers, and other food-sector businesses in Clallam and Jefferson counties, Washington. The project will help North Olympic Peninsula Resource Conservation and Development Council (NODC) supply intensive, individualized technical assistance, resources, and training to these businesses. It is expected to create four jobs and save 12 jobs.

funding_code: CF ARP EMERGENCY RURAL HEALTH CARE GRANTS - TRACK 1 & 2
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to expand the Port Angeles Food Bank, which provides services to 13 area food pantries, including four tribal communities. The food bank is the lead contractor for the Washington State Department of Agriculture Emergency Food assistance program for Clallam County. The grantee has added a kitchen to the new facility to meet the increased need and these funds will help support this necessary expansion and provide the ability to provide grab and go foods for the clientele. The kitchen will also reduce waste by using the donated food that is close to pull date and adding ready to eat meals to the freezer section. This enables the food bank to provide services with compassion and respect with a commitment to promote healthy eating.

funding_code: CF ARP EMERGENCY RURAL HEALTH CARE GRANTS - TRACK 1 & 2
naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase two power lift gurneys. The equipment will enhance Clallam Fire District 4s ability to better serve the district through distribution of COVID-19 vaccinations, COVID-19 testing, and implementation of the Community Health Triage Program while significantly improving the safety of the emergency medical staff (EMS) staff and their ability to respond to emergency calls on the Olympic Peninsula.

funding_code: CF ARP EMERGENCY RURAL HEALTH CARE GRANTS - TRACK 1 & 2
naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase an ambulance and necessary equipment for Clallam Fire District 2 that will enhance their ability to service the community through distribution of COVID-19 vaccinations, COVID-19 testing, and implementation of the Community Health Triage Program while significantly improving the safety of the emergency medical services staff and their ability to respond to emergency calls. Due to the rural nature of the area and unforeseen circumstances, a four-by-four vehicle is required to access some of the most venerable residents. This underserved community relies on Fire District # 2 for more than just fire and Ambulance coverage but full community support. All throughout the year, Fire District #2 ensures that local families are not forgotten by providing full-service help with disaster training and preparedness readiness, due to its location on the peninsula. This Fire Department and staff of Volunteers take their sense of community to the next level, and it is great to be able to offer them our support.

funding_code: FY22 CONGRESSIONALLY DIRECTED SPENDING
naics_industry_sector: Manufacturing (31-33)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to fund a building purchase, for the expansion of the Port Angeles Food Bank, which provides services to 13 area food pantries, including four tribal communities, with an estimated service area of over 71,000. They are also the lead contractor for the Washington State Department of Agriculture Emergency Food assistance program for Clallam County. The applicant has had to move to a new facility to meet the increased need and these funds will help support this necessary expansion and provide the space they need to build the foundation for sustaining the increased operation levels. This enables the food bank to provide services with compassion and respect with a commitment to promote healthy eating. This mission, project and location match the specific award in the 2022 Consolidated Appropriations Act. This project utilizes Congressional Directed Spending funds.

funding_code: (LOAN ONLY) WATER ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to replace compromised water lines and build a new reservoir to meet state regulatory requirements. The project will provide clean safe drinking water for the city of Woodland. The proposed Reservoir No. 4 includes construction of a new 1.5 million gallons reservoir on property owned by the city of Woodland to provide storage and needed service pressure to meet anticipated peak day and fire flow demands. The project also proposes to replace a total of approximately 14,500 linear feet of six-inch to 12" asbestos-cement (AC) water lines in 17 locations within the city of Woodland. total cost of the project is$18,251,019.

naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to help fund the construction of a facility for the expansion of the DJH Kids Community Center in Ilwaco, Pacific County, Washington. The mission of DJH Kids and Community Center is to strengthen the foundations of the community by offering developmental programs that connect our youth with mentors and leaders, by providing access to facilities which afford our community the opportunity to engage in recreational, sports-related, and community-driven activities in a fun environment, and to foster, nourish, and provide for the safety, health, and welfare of our youth. The total project cost for the eligible portion of the project is $3,090,375.00 with applicant contribution of $1,815,375.00. This cost is for a multi-use educational building with a gymnasium that is part of Phase one of the total project.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to help Sunny Dene Ranch LLC, located in rural Yakima County, purchase and install a 1002.96 kW solar array. project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to assist a Rural Small Business with purchasing and installing a renewable energy system. This project will replace 20,160 kilowatt hours (kWh), which is 103 percent of their energy use per year which is enough to power one home.
